LogMessage: CMM OSPF neighbor state change for %: INIT to 2WAY
LogMeaning: OSPF neighborship process 2/6. This switch has received a HELLO packet containing its own Router ID from the neighbor referenced in the log. Both sides can talk to each other

LogMessage: CMM OSPF neighbor state change for %: LOADING to FULL
LogMeaning: OSPF neighborship process 6/6. The adjacency with the neighbor has been fully completed.

LogMessage: CMM OSPF neighbor state change for %: FULL to DOWN
LogMeaning: The OSPF neighborship has gone down. This can occur if this switch has not received a HELLO packet from the neighbor with in the Dead Interval time.

Unclear. I believe it means that the interface that received the HELLO packet is not associated with any of the networks in the NetworkLSA. This would be caused by a misconfiguration, an IP interface being disconnected or an OSPF packet being sent to the wrong place

LogMessage: CMM OSPF neighbor state change for %: EXSTART to 2WAY
LogMeaning: There was a problem during the DBD packet exchange. This may be caused by an MTU mismatch or a loss of communication during the exchange

LogMessage: CMM OSPF neighbor state change for %: FULL to INIT
LogMeaning: The OSPF neighborship has gone down. This switch has received a HELLO packet that did not contain its own Router ID. This means that the neighbor is not receiving packets from this switch. The neighbor would list their state as DOWN

A MAC Address and Port were associated with a VLAN. This is a normal part of a VLAN assignment or port coming up. If you see a lot of these messages, you may have a problem with Interface flapping or VLAN flapping

A MAC Address and IP address are no longer associated with a port. This is normal if an interface has been removed from a VLAN. It also means that all interfaces associated with a given VLAN have gone down. This may be caused by an STP dispute. The log only contains the IP address but not the MAC or VLAN. Look for an `rtrmac release` log that contains this info.
